Explanation:

- I inspected controllers/invoices.js and routes/invoices.js. The POST /invoices route is handled by createInvoice (routes/invoices.js: router.post('/', createInvoice)).
- createInvoice reads req.body, constructs a new InvoiceModel(invoice), saves it, and on success responds with status 201 and the saved invoice object (JSON). On error it responds with status 409 and the error message as a plain JSON value.
- The saved invoice's structure follows models/InvoiceModel.js. I used the fields defined there to describe the 201 response schema: dueDate (date-time string), currency (string), items (array of item objects with itemName, unitPrice, quantity, discount strings), rates (string), vat (number), total (number), subTotal (number), notes (string), status (string), invoiceNumber (string), type (string), creator (array of strings), totalAmountReceived (number), client (object with name/email/phone/address strings), paymentRecords (array of objects with amountPaid number, datePaid date-time string, paymentMethod/note/paidBy strings), and createdAt (date-time string).
- For the 409 response I reflected the actual implementation which returns the error message as a JSON value (a string).
- I included only the response codes and schemas that are clearly produced by the POST /invoices handler (201 and 409) and did not add other codes or $ref references.

